We have imbalanced classes. We will rank our models on the basis of f1-score, since we don't have any information about what is more important here - precision or recall

Data Cleanup¶

Education and education-num are identical.

Relationship takes care of marital-status.
Native-country should not really matter. Besides, there are too many categories there to encode in any useful way.

In [6]:
todrop = list(['education','native-country','marital-status'])
df = df.drop(todrop,axis=1)

#replacing ? in workclass with mode of column
df['workclass']=df['workclass'].replace(' ?',df['workclass'].mode()[0])

num_cols = df.select_dtypes(np.number).columns.tolist()
cat_cols = list(set(df.columns.tolist())-set(num_cols))
cat_cols.remove('Income')

Let's simplify the categorical columns a bit¶

Workclass: Private or not private
Race: white or not white (I know, super-racist. But the data reflects that whites have a higher proportion of people earning >50K.)
Relationship: married, not-married
Occupation: (Exec-manegerial, Prof-speciality) vs others. this takes care of the '?'s in occupation. These two professions have the highest proportion of people earning >50K

In [9]:
def simplify_categories(df):
    workclass_pvt = df['workclass'].loc[df['workclass']==' Private'].index
    workclass_notpvt = df['workclass'].loc[df['workclass']!=' Private'].index
    df.loc[workclass_pvt,'workclass'] = 1
    df.loc[workclass_notpvt,'workclass'] = 0

    race_w = df['race'].loc[df['race']==' White'].index
    race_nw = df['race'].loc[df['race']!=' White'].index
    df.loc[race_w,'race']=0
    df.loc[race_nw,'race']=1

    rel_m = df['relationship'].loc[(df['relationship']==' Husband') | (df['relationship']==' Wife')].index #married
    rel_nm = df['relationship'].loc[(df['relationship']!=' Husband') & (df['relationship']!=' Wife')].index #not-married
    df.loc[rel_m,'relationship'] = 1
    df.loc[rel_nm,'relationship'] = 0

    df['sex'] = df['sex'].replace({' Male':0,' Female':1})

    occ_ep = df['occupation'].loc[(df['occupation']==' Exec-managerial') | (df['occupation']==' Prof-specialty')].index 
    #exec-managerial or prof-specialty
    occ_nep = df['occupation'].loc[(df['occupation']!=' Exec-managerial') & (df['occupation']!=' Prof-specialty')].index
    #NOT (exec-managerial or prof-specialty)
    df.loc[occ_ep,'occupation'] = 1
    df.loc[occ_nep,'occupation'] = 0
    return df

df = simplify_categories(df)
df[cat_cols] = df[cat_cols].astype(int)

Processing the Data for Fitting¶

In [12]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

trainX, testX, trainY, testY = train_test_split(df.drop('Income',axis=1),df['Income'],test_size=0.2,random_state=2)

scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaler.fit(trainX)

X_train = scaler.transform(trainX)
X_test = scaler.transform(testX)

le = LabelEncoder()
le.fit(trainY)

y_train = le.transform(trainY)
y_test = le.transform(testY)

In [14]:
classifiers = [LogisticRegression(), GaussianNB(), SVC(), DecisionTreeClassifier(),
               RandomForestClassifier(),
               LGBMClassifier(), XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False), CatBoostClassifier(verbose=False)]

scores = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Classifier','Test_f1','Train_f1','TestAccuracy','TrainAccuracy'])

for i in classifiers:
    i.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred_test = i.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_train = i.predict(X_train)
    scores.loc[len(scores.index)] = [i.__class__.__name__,
                                     f1_score(y_test,y_pred_test),f1_score(y_train,y_pred_train),
                                     accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred_test),accuracy_score(y_train,y_pred_train)]

In [16]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

y_pred_test = classifiers[5].predict(X_test)
y_pred_train = classifiers[5].predict(X_train)

cm_test = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred_test,normalize='true')
cm_train = confusion_matrix(y_train,y_pred_train,normalize='true')

fig, (ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(12,6))
fig.suptitle("LGBMClassifier\n Confusion Matrix for Test and Train Sets")
sns.heatmap(cm_test,cbar=True,annot=True,cmap='Reds',square=True,ax=ax1)
ax1.set_title("Test Set")
sns.heatmap(cm_train,cbar=True,annot=True,cmap='Reds',square=True,ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title("Train Set")
plt.show()

The confusion matrices are normalized along the rows, which means the diagonals represent the recall score wrt to that row. As expected, the minority class has poor recall score. We can over-sample the minority class and refit the model. That should give us a better result

Over-sampling the Minority Class ( >50K) in the Training Set¶

In [17]:
traindf = pd.concat([trainX,pd.DataFrame(trainY)],axis=1) 

n0, n1 = traindf['Income'].value_counts()

class0 = traindf[traindf['Income']==' <=50K']
class1 = traindf[traindf['Income']==' >50K']
In [18]:
print("Before Sampling: ")
print("Fraction of >50K (class 1): {}".format(n1/(n0+n1)))

class1over = class1.sample(int(2.5*n1),replace=True) 
overdf = pd.concat([class0,class1over],axis=0).sample(frac=1)

print("After Sampling")
print("Fraction of >50K (class 1): {}".format(overdf['Income'].value_counts()[1]/overdf.shape[0]))
